\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VC (venture capitalists) prefer the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

all-star
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 underwriters so that after IPO, the stock price is stable until the end
 of 
\emph on
lock-up 
\emph default
period so that VC can quit and earn profits.
 This is called 
\emph on
analyst lust theory
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
For underwriters:
\emph default
 In addition to IPO commission fee of 7%, underwriters can benefit from
 IPO underpricing in two ways: (i) allocate underpricing shares to investors
 and (ii) allocate underpricing shares to executives (spinning effect).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
For issuer side:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Issuers objective function: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}NetIPOproceeds+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\alpha_{i}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
 Besides the proceeds, issuers could receive non-price dimensions such as
 analyst coverage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among N underwriters, only 3 have an all-star analysts, which market value
 of being covered by all-star analysts is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Issuers have different preference parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 over all-star analyst service, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\sim Uniform[0;1]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An issuer's net surplus from going public at underpricing level 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M-U+\theta A
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is market value of shares sold net the commission fee (spread) 7% to underwrite
rs, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is underpricing money (what left on table), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta A$
\end_inset

 is effect of all-star analyst coverage on perceived value 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
For underwriter side:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The profit underwriters earn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}=(\gamma(U-\overline{U})-C)D_{k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 is dollar amount of underpricing needed to compensate investors for uncertainty
 of IPO issue valuation (assumed to be the same across issues); 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is cost of providing all-star analyst coverage (
\begin_inset Formula $C=0$
\end_inset

 for other 
\begin_inset Formula $N-3$
\end_inset

 underwriters); and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 is demand for underwriter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 services.
 A fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the incremental money of underpricing flows back to underwriters through
 indirect channels (from other firms or from executives, when allocate underpric
ed shares to them).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\bar under
No collusion (noncooperation case)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If N is large, then the N-3 underwriters without an all-star analysts will
 not be able to charge 
\begin_inset Formula $U-\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 because they are in a perfect competitive market (large number of underwriters
 with homogenous services).
 They will set 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\overline{U}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the three underwriters with all-star analysts do not cooperate, 
\series bold
under Bertrand competition
\series default
, they will charge: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\overline{U}+(C/\gamma)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Under Cornot competition
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aggregate demand: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{D}=1-\frac{\ddot{U}-\overline{U}}{A}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{U}=A+\overline{U}-A\ddot{D}=A+\overline{U}-A(q_{1}+q_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}=(\gamma(\ddot{U}-\overline{U})-C)q_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}=(\gamma(\ddot{U}-\overline{U})-C)q_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}=\ddot{q}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{q}=\frac{\gamma A-C}{3\gamma A}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{U}=A+\overline{U}-2A\ddot{q}=A+\overline{U}-2A\frac{\gamma A-C}{3\gamma A}=A+\overline{U}-\frac{2}{3}A+\frac{2C}{3\gamma}=\frac{A}{3}+\overline{U}+\frac{2C}{3\gamma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{U}=\frac{A}{3}+\overline{U}+\frac{2C}{3\gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\bar under
Under collusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If three underwriters collude and charge the same underpricing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{U}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the aggregate demand for their service can be calculated by finding
 an issuer that is 
\emph on
indifferent between choosing an underwriter with or without and all-star
 anlyst
\emph default
.
 It occurs when:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M-\mathring{U}+\hat{\theta}A=M-\bar{U}$
\end_inset

 (right-hand is surplus from allstar analysts; left-hand is from a normal
 one)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate demand is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{D}=1-\hat{\theta}=1-\frac{\mathring{U}-\overline{U}}{A}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\mathring{D}}{\partial\mathring{U}}=1-1/A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allstar underwriters choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{U}$
\end_inset

 to maximize their profits:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{\pi}=(\gamma(\mathring{U}-\overline{U})-C)\mathring{D}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FOC: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\pi}{\partial\mathring{U}}=\gamma\mathring{D}+(\gamma(\mathring{U}-\overline{U})-C)\frac{\partial\mathring{D}}{\partial\mathring{U}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\mathring{D}}{\partial\mathring{U}}=1-1/A$
\end_inset

 to FOC, we solve: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{U}=\overline{U}+\frac{\gamma A+C}{2\gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
\bar under
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\sim e(1)$
\end_inset

 with cumulative density function 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\theta),$
\end_inset

 what is 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 now?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\sim Uniform[0;1]$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is also equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (not sure).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\emph on
\bar under

\begin_inset Formula $\theta\sim e(1)$
\end_inset


\emph default
\bar default
, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}=1-E(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

